title: Grateful Dead Live at Fillmore East on 1970-02-11
description:
Early Show: The Other One > Cryptical Envelopment, Dire Wolf, Casey Jones

Late Show: Not Fade Away, Cumberland Blues, Cold Rain & Snow, High Time, Me & My Uncle, Dark Star > Spanish Jam* > Turn On Your Love Light**

Encore: Uncle John's Band

reviews.review_text: Dark Star>Spanish Jam>Lovelight Joined on stage by Peter Green of Fleetwood Mac, and most of the Allman Brothers, this section of the show is one of the best examples of the genius of the Grateful Dead. The cut in Dark Star is a huge pity. As for the Spanish Jam, words can't do it justice.

A Must Have... A must have for any fan of Grateful Dead improv!
For the amount of musicians on stage giving it their all, it still sounds very tight. No one trying to overstage anyone here- the music flows well. Very fun, wish I was there.

Crush your face This is powerful stuff.

I used to have a very poor recording that was just the spanish jam>lovelight

Now I know and understand...everytime the allman bros. and the dead got together was a special time.  No exception here.  Pure rage.
start burning If your reading this and not downloading, shame on you.  The music speaks for itself.  The dark Star cut is ashame, but this show still holds great value

Top 5! Unbelieveably, the Dead played the Fillmore East TWICE in the winter of 70,a Jan and Feb run of shows which, in my opinion, may be the best of the entire year. This show is a "dress rehersal" for their monster 2-night stand on the 13th & 14th when they were touring with the Allmans.
I was stunned the first time I heard this tape, and it never fails to delight and astound years later. The sheer energy and excitement come thru in every song. Scorching versions of Cumberland, NFA and the Other One. And the Dark Star is just about as perfect as can be, stellar sound quality and great ensemble playing by the guys. The addition of Duane, Greg and Peter Green on the jams and Lovelight really makes this "one of those nights". Even with all the cuts, this show makes my top 5. A show that must be cranked up to be appreciated! Enjoy.
Dr. Flashback ;-)
The Ship of the Dead... ...is driven by Phil Lesh...the Spanish Jam>Lovelight is all the proof you need...although every musician smokes on this monster performance, it is Phil who leads the way...

Must Have Nothing like being considered the weak sister of arguably the best Dead run ever.  Will always be overshadowed by the 2/13-14 shows but does stand on it's own very well.  Could have been released as a follow up to DP IV but the cuts make it tough as a comercial release.

Great sound recording just like you were there on the lower east side but the cuts do stink.  The layers of musicians make the Dark Star on ward very cool.  Spanish Jam is especially fun and the Lovelight would have to be classified as a top 10.
As hard hitting as an uppercut from Tyson No words for this just listen to Lovelight and the rest with the Allman Brothers. They sure loved NYC....

UJB This is a precious version of Uncle John's Band.  The harmony in the vocals is gorgeous, and the single acoustic guitar is practically perfect.

The sound quality is fresh and the hiss is minimal.  Just as vital a recording as 2-13/14 '70

SoundQuality No doubt this was a real monster performance,but
is completely ruined by the near abscence of peter green in the mix.If Bear wasn't concerned about other musicians other than the dead,why is duane allman so audible but green isn't?What
possible excuse could he have for mixing such 
an incendiary talent out of the sound?
It reduces the show to incompleteness and is 
most annoying.Simply not worth having
just on the basis of frustration.Anybody know
of any good soundboards that have a good representation of all three guitarists,none seem to?  
A show that is ruined by poor sound quality.

mo duane i once had this on a bad aud. tape......still can't hear anyone but the dead...i imagine it wasn't a concern of Bear's to get their amps in the recording mix          i don't mind    Jerry will slay and did        the dead are in top form here........the best! the recording starts off with the other one.....the quality is as  brilliant as the playing-----5 i do hear a little distorting going on---could just be jerry's twins arguing with the snare chains     hmmm     this direwolf is very nice quality dead----

oh baby, just listen to the lovelight.....
let it shine indeed!!!! 
Is there anyway we can seed the 12-31-73 show, at least set 2-3 with the dead and abb ????
I would love to get a copy of that one 
Eric

Super Nova Hereafter, it doesn't get much better/hotter (Port Chester) than this, ladies & gentlemen. Since when did Alhambra's Spanish Jam sting like cayenne? No need to mention the Lovelight with all the players well represented in turn according to heirarchy. The lone guitar on UJB amidst all those raving FillE's is perfect.

cast Arthur Lee of Love adds percussion to the Dark Star. The third guitarist audible starting about 2:30 into Dark Star and for several minutes thereafter is Peter Green. Duane Allman on slide guitar enters around the middle of Dark Star. Gregg Allman adds organ & vocals during Lovelight, and Barry Oakley plays a second bass on Lovelight. Richard Pipes believes Fleetwood Mac-member Danny Kirwan's guitar is also to be discerned in the background. The encore is acoustic Dead, with only one acoustic guitar. The timings are from the AUD supplemented by the SBD. The Allman Bros and Love were also on the bill.

Monster show There is little doubt that this show has an all-time best Lovelight. It just cooks and cooks and cooks. It's better than 2/13/70, IMO. Greg Allman's vocals are just so soulful and Peter Green rips up some licks that are guaranteed to make hair stand up on your head. In fact, the Lovelight is so strong that the rest of the show pretty much pales in comparison, even the Dark Star>Spanish jam.

Speaking of DS, the cut at 6:58 or so is irritating. There are SBDs circulating that have the missing 3 minutes or so, so why not patch the gap and make a composite?! Plus, the second half of DS after the cut runs at a slower speed than the 1st half, which makes the cut jarring to say the least. Until a composite surfaces, this otherwise excellent show gets only 4 out of 5 stars.
sooo crispy sound quality alone makes the dl worthwhile...

Phil says it all himself! From his autobiography:
Someone opens the loading dock behind the stage. I walk outside - its daylight...The other musicians straggle out...I grab Bobby and Jerry and in a group embrace: This is what it's all about.

Sweet  x4 YESSSSSSS!  Best Lovelight ever to be played in the history of mankind (34 minutes of godlyness).  Gregg and Duane Allman and Berry Oakley.  Unbelievable.  If only the Allman Bros. Band were on this sight. Not to mention, Jerry is playing abnormally well. The epitome of fucking amazing. eighty five stars

P.S. It is not a major loss that Dark Star is cut, but it may piss you off.

PLEASE PATCH DARK STAR This show is top level everything, and the dark star is sickeningly good...except I don't know how we got where we ended up....I guess I will go find a complete version and quite complaining, but for the sake of those who cannot, please patch the dark star. Despite the missing section, this show re-inforces the need for a 10 star rating system...no way are there more than a handful that touch it. MONITORS HEY WE'VE GOT MONITORS, ITS THE MONITORS...GOD BLESS THE ARCHIVE...so Phil writes about this his book huh? I have been meandering through it slowly a few pages at a time...no suprise that he mentions this one though. 
5 for playing 
4.5 for  sound <--patch :)

allman brothers-period this is the best lovelight version i have ever heard. greggs voice is awesome and duane's slide is on fire. the dead made a great choice in inviting the allman brothers and peter green to this show. unbelievable

pass the cheese!!! i'm literally cooking a grilled cheese sandwich over the flames coming out of my speakers!! comes with side of allman brothers and garcia hot sauce!download and inhale before it taken off the menu!      mm..mm..mm..gooood!!

the music is still in my head as with all live tapes one can wish for completeness. what was there of dark star was great. lovelight was sublime. peter green, duane allman, danny, dickey and bob being sheparded by jerry into musical bliss. Don't you wish you could go back in time. great Me and my uncle
duuhhh I grew upon Ludlow ave. Duane was a god in my hood.This is the mutha uf all lovelights...But I feel so happy when I hear the UncleJohn's  acoustic encore

Truly amazing! These 2 sets are where it's at!  Shame on GDM for taking these SBDs away from us.  They were there and then they were f-ing gone.  Luckily, I managed to get more shows than I can manage....but I missed this one, and now it's too f-ing late.  Shame on you GDM.  I buy stuff from you (DP/s and DL series) and you take away these amazing shows for your profits.  

Anyway, I'm streaming this show right now and it is just smokin'.  DAMN!  The jam about 2/3 into Dark Star is just SICK....so dark and mean.  Early 1970 dead is f-ing unreal!  Sound is crystal clear.

foresight I wish I had the foresight to grab this one...If you know someone who has the shn. files of this show , get it.  The streamin audio sounds crystal clear; not bad for the computer speaker configuration.  This show is a gem from start to finish.  1970 rocked!!!

Better than alright This must be the Lovelight I've been avoiding with lesser quality one's.
You add the Allman's to it and it has more movement.

Pictured Guests Based on a picture in the "The Deadhead's Tape Compendium Volume 1," the following people were on stage: Mick Fleetwood-dancing, Peter Green-guitar, Pigpen-vocals, Bob Weir-guitar/vocals, Danny Kirwin-guitar, Gregg Allman-organ/vocals, Jerry Garcia-guitar, Bill Kreutzmann-drum kit, Berry Oakley-bass, Butch Trucks-drum kit, Duane Allman-guitar, Mickey Hart-percussion.  Phil Lesh is not pictured.  The photo is likely of "Lovelight."  I just found a link to the CD cover with the photo: http://www.geocities.com/deadpieshop3/covers/gd700211_back.jpg

dark star haunts me What I wouldn't do to hear a complete, non-spliced copy of this show. The highlight is the Dark Star, which gets overshadowed by the version from 2/13 (understandably). But despite a jagged gap in the middle, this jam is wild! bobby is the commanding presence as they rock through dark star and into the only spanish jam between 1969 and 1973. Truly a legendary show.

Must listen show Well, there are a bunch of cuts which ordinarily wouldn't permit me to give a show 5 stars, originally I gave this show a 4.  But after much listening to it, I changed my opinion. The playing is fantastic and the sound is pretty darn good too. 

And talk about guest stars. The Darkstar is facinating due to the addition of Peter Green, and Duane Allman on guitar and Arthur Lee from Love on percussion. It's much funkier and groove oriented than how the Dead normally play it. During Lovelight Butch Trucks gets on Mickey's drum kit, Mick plays percussion, Barry Oakley plays second bass, Peter Green and Duane Allman play guitar, and Greg Allman joins on organ and vocals. Pig and Greg trade off lines and everybody jams their asses off, incredible. Some people claim that Danny Kirwan is on stage as well but I've seen pictures and I think people are confusing him with Phil. They both have very blond hair and Phil's back is turned to the camera. (Well Phil says otherwise so I gotta go with him, after reading his book) Anyway, Mick Fleetwood is dancing stage right. Fantastic show, goddamn, Bob and Jerry are pushing it.

Spanish Jam The second set starts with a brilliant 'Not Fade Away' but as soon as the Allman Bros and miscellaneous co. join the stage during 'Dark Star' the show begins to peak. 

Sadly, however, the middle is cut right out of 'Dark Star' and in the midst of a groovy intro, we are jumped into a bizarre landscape which transcends into...the Spanish Jam! 

1970 never ceases to amaze me and this night is no exception because as much as the Dead were flying forward with a new identity, they were also reaching back into the past (sometimes for the last time).  A somewhat short lived jam from the early 68 tour, Spanish Jam is a glorious dark abyss.

Like I said, the cut in Dark Star is vicious, but after listening to the Spanish Jam, I imagine to myself that the Dark Star jam must have been so divine that it could never be recorded.

to paraphrase phil.... Was reading “Searching for the Sound” and had to look up this show after Phil talked about it… and i can see why he devoted almost 3 pages to it. here are some notes I took from the book as I was listening:
•	Jerry says to Phil of the ABB on their way to this show: “make sure you check these guys out… they’re kinda like us… They jam hard”
•	Phil was startled when he heard Duane’s slide during Dark Star… Jerry hadn’t told him anyone would sit in
•	Gregg “slides onto the organ bench” during Spanish Jam
•	“Peter Green from the Mac plugs in just as I’m pulling the music into the dominant minor … he and Duane seem more comfortable in this space.”
•	Butch joins on drums
•	Mickey attacks his gigantic gong
•	Mick Fleetwood and Danny Kirwan “find room to join the festivities”
•	“it’s a surprisingly coherent free-for-all, with five guitarists , four drummers, organ, and – Pigpen roaring over it all”
•	“Gregg takes a verse … Sounding like a fifty-year-old black man even then.”
•	Pig and Gregg trade vocals
•	Berry Oakley takes over on bass about halfway through Lovelight as Phil just wants to listen
•	There’s a smokestack theme running throughout
•	“my mind starts to stretch out of shape… Everyone on stage is flat-out wailing”

After the show, “I walk outside – it’s daylight, and snow is falling gently on the streets of New York… I grab Bob and Jerry in a group embrace: This is what it’s all about.”

great, historic jam but not as good as GD... I watched this from the front row of the mezzanine (my ticket was for the upper deck but the Fillmore was only about 1/3 full, so I was able to go down to the front of the mezzanine, on the right).  A local guy from the same town as me, Englewood New Jersey, was taping this on a cassette tape next to me; I don't know if his tape is one of the ones here in archive.org.

The jam was incredible, with the guitarists trading licks the way (I later learned) jazz musicians do -- each replaying part of the previous musician's improv and then adding his own extension to it and passing it along.  But even so, it seemed to me then, and it seems to me now, that the musicians, because they were not as familiar with each other as the Dead themselves were, played a much simpler kind of riff for each other. 

It was great -- incredible -- that they invented music on the fly the way they did.  But they did not have the telepathic understanding of each other that the Grateful Dead musicians did, so the music itself was less interesting, less exploratory, than "regular" Dead music.

I was and am completely happy to have been present at this historic concert.  But my sense of the Dead having to "play down to" a collection of good, but unfamiliar, musicians was borne out on Friday the 13th, when the Dead followed an unbelievable Allman Brothers set -- which had me thinking that there was no way the Dead could top that, in terms of improvisation and sheer musical chops -- and then they did their Dark Star/ Other One/ Lovelight sequence and just redefined the range of possibilities for improvisational rock music.  They took a great, great ABB set and turned it into the motivation to create a transcendent Grateful Dead set that no one but the Dead could ever come close to...  Or so it seemed to me at the time.

Great music here, and legendary musicians and collaboration.  But "there is nothing like a Grateful Dead concert," as the saying went..
